00:01:15.376 --> 00:01:18.126
(ethereal music)

00:01:20.541 --> 00:01:23.124
(upbeat music)

00:01:39.816 --> 00:01:42.379
- I'm gonna give you a little
bit of a break from the brain

00:01:42.379 --> 00:01:44.212
and focus on the face.

00:01:45.995 --> 00:01:49.306
So, a central, if in fact
not the central question

00:01:49.306 --> 00:01:51.210
in modern biology is to understand

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:53.634
the genotype to phenotype connection.

00:01:53.634 --> 00:01:55.693
In other words, how does information

00:01:55.693 --> 00:01:58.405
encoded by the genome reveals itself

00:01:58.405 --> 00:02:00.528
through the developmental process

00:02:00.528 --> 00:02:03.074
to produce specific phenotypes?

00:02:03.074 --> 00:02:05.127
And, the flip side to this question

00:02:05.127 --> 00:02:07.873
is to understand how
variation between the genome,

00:02:07.873 --> 00:02:11.415
during evolution produces
phenotypic variation,

00:02:11.415 --> 00:02:13.716
either between species,

00:02:13.716 --> 00:02:18.053
or between individuals
within the same species.

00:02:18.053 --> 00:02:21.553
And, how come such common genetic variants

00:02:22.806 --> 00:02:25.618
can determine disease susceptibility

00:02:25.618 --> 00:02:28.239
in complex human diseases.

00:02:28.239 --> 00:02:30.346
I'm sure most of you heard by now

00:02:30.346 --> 00:02:34.220
that most complex disease
and trait associated variants

00:02:34.220 --> 00:02:37.248
not to the noncoding part of the genome.

00:02:37.248 --> 00:02:40.272
So not to our genes per se,

00:02:40.272 --> 00:02:42.069
the protein coding parts of the genome,

00:02:42.069 --> 00:02:44.101
but to the vast noncoding space

00:02:44.101 --> 00:02:47.851
that comprises over 98
percent of the genome.

00:02:49.348 --> 00:02:51.620
Moreover, evidence begins to emerge

00:02:51.620 --> 00:02:53.648
that these variants are enriched

00:02:53.648 --> 00:02:56.049
within cis-regulatory elements,

00:02:56.049 --> 00:02:58.536
and especially within a specific class

00:02:58.536 --> 00:03:01.344
of regulatory elements called enhancers.

00:03:01.344 --> 00:03:03.724
So these are modular genetic sequences

00:03:03.724 --> 00:03:07.184
that can activate gene
expression at large distances,

00:03:07.184 --> 00:03:11.186
and are typically specialized
to activate gene expression

00:03:11.186 --> 00:03:13.603
in a specific tissue context.

00:03:14.464 --> 00:03:17.471
And the idea here, is that
this genetic variance,

00:03:17.471 --> 00:03:21.028
or single nucleotide
polymorphisms within enhancers,

00:03:21.028 --> 00:03:25.483
can produce either weak or
strong enhancer alleles,

00:03:25.483 --> 00:03:28.966
which in turn, can lead to
quantitative differences

00:03:28.966 --> 00:03:33.133
in gene expression and
influence downstream traits.

00:03:34.111 --> 00:03:36.257
We learned from the evo-devo community

00:03:36.257 --> 00:03:37.980
working on model organisms

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:40.935
that starting this regulatory
landscape evolution

00:03:40.935 --> 00:03:42.822
of closely related species

00:03:42.822 --> 00:03:45.269
can be an extremely powerful tool

00:03:45.269 --> 00:03:49.004
in uncovering genotype
to phenotype connections.

00:03:49.004 --> 00:03:52.534
So for example, elegant
work from Sean Carroll,

00:03:52.534 --> 00:03:54.218
David Kingsley, and others,

00:03:54.218 --> 00:03:55.964
unequivocally demonstrated

00:03:55.964 --> 00:03:58.027
the change in enhancer sequence

00:03:58.027 --> 00:04:00.413
can dictate change in phenotypes,

00:04:00.413 --> 00:04:02.645
such as wing pattern in Drosophila,

00:04:02.645 --> 00:04:05.873
or skeletal changes in stickleback fish.

00:04:05.873 --> 00:04:07.251
And we were very interested

00:04:07.251 --> 00:04:09.905
in extending this type
of evo-devo thinking

00:04:09.905 --> 00:04:12.276
into humans and other primates.

00:04:12.276 --> 00:04:16.004
But of course, as it's
already been mentioned,

00:04:16.004 --> 00:04:18.347
some of the key developmentally

00:04:18.347 --> 00:04:20.955
and evolutionary important cell types

00:04:20.955 --> 00:04:24.325
cannot be studied directly
in embryonic context

00:04:24.325 --> 00:04:26.324
from humans and other great apes,

00:04:26.324 --> 00:04:28.657
for obvious ethical reasons,

00:04:31.729 --> 00:04:34.419
but it has already been introduced,

00:04:34.419 --> 00:04:37.484
that now with induced
pluripotent stem cell models,

00:04:37.484 --> 00:04:40.499
we can study cellular
and molecular mechanisms

00:04:40.499 --> 00:04:43.650
underlying phenotypic
divergence in high primates.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:45.589
And a few years back, we referred

00:04:45.589 --> 00:04:49.505
to this general strategy
as cellular anthropology.

00:04:49.505 --> 00:04:54.029
So one of the phenotypes that
we are most interested in,

00:04:54.029 --> 00:04:57.784
is human face and also human
craniofacial development.

00:04:57.784 --> 00:05:00.016
We know that craniofacial variation,

00:05:00.016 --> 00:05:02.328
both within and between species,

00:05:02.328 --> 00:05:04.911
is largely genetically encoded.

00:05:05.865 --> 00:05:08.101
So we have unique facial features

00:05:08.101 --> 00:05:12.621
that are distinct from
those of other great apes,

00:05:12.621 --> 00:05:14.105
but also there is a lot

00:05:14.105 --> 00:05:16.489
of individual variation in facial form,

00:05:16.489 --> 00:05:18.016
both within the humans

00:05:18.016 --> 00:05:22.157
but also in our close
evolutionary relatives.

00:05:22.157 --> 00:05:23.211
So the question is,

00:05:23.211 --> 00:05:26.630
what are the cellular
origins of facial variation?

00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:29.367
Well, it turns out that
most of our face and head

00:05:29.367 --> 00:05:31.547
is derived from the single cell type

00:05:31.547 --> 00:05:33.649
called cranial neural crest cells.

00:05:33.649 --> 00:05:37.078
These are very unique
cells that form early

00:05:37.078 --> 00:05:39.437
in gestations of three to five weeks.

00:05:39.437 --> 00:05:42.837
They're induced in dorsal
anterior part of the neural tube,

00:05:42.837 --> 00:05:45.609
and then they migrate long distances.

00:05:45.609 --> 00:05:47.167
And their destination,

00:05:47.167 --> 00:05:50.369
they can differentiate to a
large variety of cell types,

00:05:50.369 --> 00:05:53.345
including bone, cartilage,
connective tissue,

00:05:53.345 --> 00:05:55.919
cranial nerve, and pigment cells.

00:05:55.919 --> 00:05:57.610
And as a result, in fact,

00:05:57.610 --> 00:05:59.713
most of the craniofacial complex

00:05:59.713 --> 00:06:02.537
is derived from the neural crest.

00:06:02.537 --> 00:06:05.941
Moreover, seminal work
from Nicole Le Douarin,

00:06:05.941 --> 00:06:07.354
and others showed

00:06:07.354 --> 00:06:10.476
through cross species
transplantation experiments

00:06:10.476 --> 00:06:12.689
in avian embryos, that these cells

00:06:12.689 --> 00:06:15.405
autonomously carry much of the information

00:06:15.405 --> 00:06:18.619
on species specific facial morphology.

00:06:18.619 --> 00:06:19.951
So these cells are important,

00:06:19.951 --> 00:06:22.187
but how can we access them

00:06:22.187 --> 00:06:24.770
from humans and other primates?

00:06:25.765 --> 00:06:28.175
As you already probably realized,

00:06:28.175 --> 00:06:30.127
this is a tricky proposition.

00:06:30.127 --> 00:06:32.383
So, this is transient embryonic cell types

00:06:32.383 --> 00:06:34.747
forming at three to
five weeks of gestation.

00:06:34.747 --> 00:06:37.514
We cannot access them
directly from the embryo,

00:06:37.514 --> 00:06:41.520
but thanks to the IPS and ES technologies,

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:43.217
we can derive them in vitro,

00:06:43.217 --> 00:06:45.999
and indeed that's what my lab has done

00:06:45.999 --> 00:06:48.340
over the last several years
is establish protocols

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:52.907
to obtain in vitro cells
with bonafide characteristics

00:06:52.907 --> 00:06:55.909
of the cranial neural crest cells.

00:06:55.909 --> 00:06:58.196
More recently, Sara Prescott,

00:06:58.196 --> 00:07:00.216
a former graduate student in the lab,

00:07:00.216 --> 00:07:02.630
working in collaboration with Rusty Gage,

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:05.766
extended this model to our chimpanzee.

00:07:05.766 --> 00:07:08.544
And here, really a few key features were,

00:07:08.544 --> 00:07:11.454
to reduce heterogeneity of the population

00:07:11.454 --> 00:07:15.639
and properly stage human and chimp cells,

00:07:15.639 --> 00:07:18.134
because unless you do that,

00:07:18.134 --> 00:07:20.738
the developmental differences
are gonna dominate

00:07:20.738 --> 00:07:23.593
over species differences.

00:07:23.593 --> 00:07:25.682
And moreover, we also
went to great lengths

00:07:25.682 --> 00:07:29.049
so I'm sure that not only
molecular signatures,

00:07:29.049 --> 00:07:32.101
but also cellular
properties of these cells

00:07:32.101 --> 00:07:34.159
represent bona fide neural crest cells.

00:07:34.159 --> 00:07:36.605
So for example, we can
transplant these cells,

00:07:36.605 --> 00:07:38.699
through the chick embryo neural tube,

00:07:38.699 --> 00:07:40.866
and they will then engraft, migrate,

00:07:40.866 --> 00:07:44.662
and assume correct positional
identities in the embryo.

00:07:44.662 --> 00:07:46.276
And they also retain

00:07:46.276 --> 00:07:48.612
this very broad differentiation potential,

00:07:48.612 --> 00:07:50.898
characteristic of the crest.

00:07:50.898 --> 00:07:53.074
So now with this model in hand,

00:07:53.074 --> 00:07:54.584
we use epigenomic strategy

00:07:54.584 --> 00:07:57.803
to systematically annotate
regulatory elements.

00:07:57.803 --> 00:08:00.387
So just to give you an idea,

00:08:00.387 --> 00:08:04.554
for those of you who are not
so familiar with epigenomics,

00:08:05.647 --> 00:08:07.399
when active enhancers share

00:08:07.399 --> 00:08:10.042
certain common chromatin features.

00:08:10.042 --> 00:08:12.903
And when we can use
technology, like ChIP-seq

00:08:12.903 --> 00:08:15.735
or ATAC-seq to map these
features genome wide

00:08:15.735 --> 00:08:19.977
in an unbiased manner
in a specific cell type.

00:08:19.977 --> 00:08:22.230
And then, we can correlate these changes

00:08:22.230 --> 00:08:24.098
in epigenomic patterns

00:08:24.098 --> 00:08:28.265
with changes in gene expression
determined by RNA-seq.

00:08:29.833 --> 00:08:34.497
So to do this, Sara took
neural crest cells in vitro,

00:08:34.497 --> 00:08:35.858
derived neural crest cells

00:08:35.858 --> 00:08:40.025
from multiple, independent
chimp and human individuals

00:08:41.370 --> 00:08:44.171
and performed mapping
of transcription factors

00:08:44.171 --> 00:08:46.413
and general coactivators,

00:08:46.413 --> 00:08:49.222
analysis of hypersensitivity by ATAC-seq,

00:08:49.222 --> 00:08:52.965
and also analyzed certain chemical tags,

00:08:52.965 --> 00:08:56.120
or histone modifications that
are present on nucleosomes

00:08:56.120 --> 00:08:59.483
when regulatory elements are active.

00:08:59.483 --> 00:09:01.843
And based on the simple
chromatin signatures,

00:09:01.843 --> 00:09:04.395
she was able to map enhancers

00:09:04.395 --> 00:09:06.875
that are active in the neural crest cells

00:09:06.875 --> 00:09:08.630
and also distinguish them

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:11.303
from other classes of regulatory elements,

00:09:11.303 --> 00:09:15.032
such as promoters, and
then ultimately linked

00:09:15.032 --> 00:09:18.085
to differences in gene expression.

00:09:18.085 --> 00:09:19.473
One thing that I really need to mention,

00:09:19.473 --> 00:09:22.165
is that not only we can map
these regulatory elements,

00:09:22.165 --> 00:09:24.324
but that quantitative comparisons

00:09:24.324 --> 00:09:27.533
of chromatin signatures of these elements,

00:09:27.533 --> 00:09:30.571
can be used to infer
differences in their activity.

00:09:30.571 --> 00:09:33.101
So, it's not only where
these enhancers are,

00:09:33.101 --> 00:09:36.568
but we can compare quantitatively

00:09:36.568 --> 00:09:39.840
these tags, chromatin signatures

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.423
to infer how different they are

00:09:42.423 --> 00:09:45.128
in their activity between the species.

00:09:45.128 --> 00:09:47.848
So this forms the basis of what I refer to

00:09:47.848 --> 00:09:49.224
as comparative epigenomics.

00:09:49.224 --> 00:09:51.532
And the idea here is simple,

00:09:51.532 --> 00:09:54.735
that we're comparing, in the same cell,

00:09:54.735 --> 00:09:57.270
that between two closely related species.

00:09:57.270 --> 00:10:00.527
So, most of these epigenomic
patterns that we recover

00:10:00.527 --> 00:10:03.318
should be invariant
between the two species,

00:10:03.318 --> 00:10:05.814
but the idea is also that
we will be able to see

00:10:05.814 --> 00:10:09.205
some differences,
quantitative differences,

00:10:09.205 --> 00:10:13.321
in those chemical tags
that mark active chromatin,

00:10:13.321 --> 00:10:16.409
which will be indicative of the difference

00:10:16.409 --> 00:10:18.153
in regulatory activity,

00:10:18.153 --> 00:10:20.455
which then hopefully
we'll also be able to link

00:10:20.455 --> 00:10:23.226
to differences in gene expressions.

00:10:23.226 --> 00:10:24.422
So, that's the idea.

00:10:24.422 --> 00:10:26.475
How does the actual data look like?

00:10:26.475 --> 00:10:29.075
Well indeed, most of
the epigenomic patterns

00:10:29.075 --> 00:10:32.305
are invariant between human and chimp,

00:10:32.305 --> 00:10:34.167
but we also see, at the subset of,

00:10:34.167 --> 00:10:37.146
smaller subset of regions
we see differences,

00:10:37.146 --> 00:10:40.896
as indicted here in this
chimp biased region,

00:10:42.084 --> 00:10:46.515
or indicated here at this
human biased enhancer region.

00:10:46.515 --> 00:10:48.486
So we can quantify
them, these differences,

00:10:48.486 --> 00:10:50.201
across the whole genome

00:10:50.201 --> 00:10:54.360
and compare different
individuals of the same species.

00:10:54.360 --> 00:10:56.249
So, different humans or different chimps,

00:10:56.249 --> 00:10:58.866
and that variation is shown here in red.

00:10:58.866 --> 00:11:01.151
Or, we can compare between the species,

00:11:01.151 --> 00:11:02.753
between human and chimp.

00:11:02.753 --> 00:11:03.701
And as you can see,

00:11:03.701 --> 00:11:06.699
there's more variation
between the species,

00:11:06.699 --> 00:11:10.710
shown here in blue than
within the species.

00:11:10.710 --> 00:11:13.074
And we will refer to those falling outside

00:11:13.074 --> 00:11:15.021
as either human-biased

00:11:15.021 --> 00:11:18.659
or chimp-biased candidate
enhancer regions.

00:11:18.659 --> 00:11:22.943
Importantly, we can also
see these regulatory changes

00:11:22.943 --> 00:11:26.133
with changes in gene expression.

00:11:26.133 --> 00:11:29.529
So in other words, genes
near human-biased enhancers

00:11:29.529 --> 00:11:32.116
tend to be human-biased in expression,

00:11:32.116 --> 00:11:34.388
and those near chimp-biased enhancers

00:11:34.388 --> 00:11:36.259
are chimp-biased in expression.

00:11:36.259 --> 00:11:37.713
And that's of course important,

00:11:37.713 --> 00:11:39.381
because it's gene expression difference

00:11:39.381 --> 00:11:43.548
that ultimately matters for
exerting phenotypic differences.

00:11:45.152 --> 00:11:48.073
Moreover, these are not
just some random genes,

00:11:48.073 --> 00:11:50.543
but in fact when we do ontology annotation

00:11:50.543 --> 00:11:51.989
for these biased genes,

00:11:51.989 --> 00:11:54.791
we see that they're
associated with development

00:11:54.791 --> 00:11:58.279
and malformation of various
craniofacial structures,

00:11:58.279 --> 00:12:01.964
including those structures that
are actually quite divergent

00:12:01.964 --> 00:12:04.635
between human and chimp.

00:12:04.635 --> 00:12:07.541
But now, a important question to ask is,

00:12:07.541 --> 00:12:09.825
where do these interspecies differences

00:12:09.825 --> 00:12:12.555
in enhancer signatures come from?

00:12:12.555 --> 00:12:13.950
Are they due to differences

00:12:13.950 --> 00:12:16.080
in the trans-regulatory environments

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:18.823
of the human and chimp neural crest?

00:12:18.823 --> 00:12:22.169
So, different in
transcription factor networks,

00:12:22.169 --> 00:12:23.557
things like that?

00:12:23.557 --> 00:12:27.460
Or are they due to differences
in enhancer sequence itself?

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:30.284
So, cis-regulatory changes.

00:12:30.284 --> 00:12:33.120
And to distinguish between
these two possibilities,

00:12:33.120 --> 00:12:35.362
we designed the following assay.

00:12:35.362 --> 00:12:38.717
We synthesized the library
of orthologous regions,

00:12:38.717 --> 00:12:41.986
that were either
human-biased, chimp-biased,

00:12:41.986 --> 00:12:44.857
or invariant in our epigenomic data.

00:12:44.857 --> 00:12:46.463
And then we cloned this library

00:12:46.463 --> 00:12:49.885
to a so-called self-transcribing
enhancer reporter vector

00:12:49.885 --> 00:12:52.165
forming the basis of the STARR-seq,

00:12:52.165 --> 00:12:55.348
as he described two years
backed by Alex Stark's lab,

00:12:55.348 --> 00:12:57.945
and which relies on
the ability of enhancer

00:12:57.945 --> 00:13:00.786
to activate its own
expression at a distance,

00:13:00.786 --> 00:13:02.950
and then drive its own expression

00:13:02.950 --> 00:13:05.150
and serve as its own barcode.

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:08.571
And we took this library and
introduced it to either chimp,

00:13:08.571 --> 00:13:10.953
or human neural crest cells.

00:13:10.953 --> 00:13:13.550
From this, we learned
two important things.

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:17.050
First of all, bias in epigenomic signature

00:13:19.447 --> 00:13:23.329
translates into the bias and
ability of these sequences

00:13:23.329 --> 00:13:25.534
to drive gene expression.

00:13:25.534 --> 00:13:29.339
In other words, what we
predicted as human-biased,

00:13:29.339 --> 00:13:32.244
which you should be seeing
here, was human-biased.

00:13:32.244 --> 00:13:35.102
And what we predicted as chimp-biased,

00:13:35.102 --> 00:13:36.926
was chimp-biased in general

00:13:36.926 --> 00:13:40.554
in the ability to drive gene expression.

00:13:40.554 --> 00:13:42.443
And the second important conclusion

00:13:42.443 --> 00:13:45.354
was the direction of
the bias was the same,

00:13:45.354 --> 00:13:48.007
whether we tested our
library in the context

00:13:48.007 --> 00:13:51.424
of the human or chimp neural crest cells.

00:13:52.603 --> 00:13:56.143
And what this tells us, is
that the bias is encoded

00:13:56.143 --> 00:13:58.713
by the sequence of enhancers themselves,

00:13:58.713 --> 00:14:00.923
rather than imposed by the differences

00:14:00.923 --> 00:14:03.816
in trans-regulatory environments.

00:14:03.816 --> 00:14:05.338
So if it's in the sequence,

00:14:05.338 --> 00:14:07.773
and the trans-regulatory environments

00:14:07.773 --> 00:14:10.720
are more conserved, we can go as far as

00:14:10.720 --> 00:14:13.394
to the trans-regulatory
environment of the mouse,

00:14:13.394 --> 00:14:16.232
to gain some insight where,

00:14:16.232 --> 00:14:18.677
when and where during development

00:14:18.677 --> 00:14:21.165
these enhancers may be active.

00:14:21.165 --> 00:14:23.969
And here, I'm showing a
couple of examples of this,

00:14:23.969 --> 00:14:27.803
where we're looking at
the human-biased enhancer,

00:14:27.803 --> 00:14:29.996
and we're cloning orthologous sequence

00:14:29.996 --> 00:14:32.234
from either human or chimp

00:14:32.234 --> 00:14:34.127
to the LacZ enhancer reporter vector,

00:14:34.127 --> 00:14:37.346
and testing in the context
of the mouse embryo.

00:14:37.346 --> 00:14:39.682
And why there is a shared expression

00:14:39.682 --> 00:14:41.608
in the olfactory placode,

00:14:41.608 --> 00:14:45.358
there is a human-associated
gain in multiple,

00:14:46.892 --> 00:14:50.642
in multiple domains
within the head and face.

00:14:51.849 --> 00:14:53.416
And here is another example,

00:14:53.416 --> 00:14:55.525
again, a human-biased enhancer.

00:14:55.525 --> 00:14:57.821
This one is more pan-neural crest.

00:14:57.821 --> 00:15:00.914
And again, you see the gain of activity

00:15:00.914 --> 00:15:02.943
for the human sequence.

00:15:02.943 --> 00:15:05.397
And this one is actually quite blazing in,

00:15:05.397 --> 00:15:07.269
in the face, whereas the chimp,

00:15:07.269 --> 00:15:10.612
corresponding chimp
sequence is not active.

00:15:10.612 --> 00:15:13.153
So, this is interesting because it shows

00:15:13.153 --> 00:15:15.733
that we can systematically
identify enhancers

00:15:15.733 --> 00:15:18.750
that change the regulatory activity,

00:15:18.750 --> 00:15:20.983
during recent human evolution,

00:15:20.983 --> 00:15:22.745
and we can even learn something

00:15:22.745 --> 00:15:26.721
about their spatial temporal
activity during development,

00:15:26.721 --> 00:15:29.446
but what this type of
work will not tell us

00:15:29.446 --> 00:15:32.532
is whether these enhancers
are actually responsible

00:15:32.532 --> 00:15:36.747
for driving variation
in facial morphology.

00:15:36.747 --> 00:15:38.797
And while we can model
some of these aspects

00:15:38.797 --> 00:15:40.628
of variation in the mouse,

00:15:40.628 --> 00:15:42.800
again mouse is not an ideal system

00:15:42.800 --> 00:15:45.891
for studying human facial variation.

00:15:45.891 --> 00:15:49.254
So to try addressing these questions,

00:15:49.254 --> 00:15:51.898
we thought about harnessing glorious

00:15:51.898 --> 00:15:54.278
normal-range human facial variation,

00:15:54.278 --> 00:15:58.373
which you can see just
looking around this room,

00:15:58.373 --> 00:16:00.827
and our ability to noninvasively

00:16:00.827 --> 00:16:03.436
and quite precisely quantify it.

00:16:03.436 --> 00:16:05.270
And to do this, we teamed up

00:16:05.270 --> 00:16:08.763
with a group of
anthropologists, engineers,

00:16:08.763 --> 00:16:10.486
and human geneticists,

00:16:10.486 --> 00:16:13.392
who developed a very novel methodology

00:16:13.392 --> 00:16:15.932
for unbiased facial phenotyping.

00:16:15.932 --> 00:16:19.514
And, I just wanna mention
at least three names,

00:16:19.514 --> 00:16:23.753
Peter Claes, Mark Shriver,
and Seth Weinberg.

00:16:23.753 --> 00:16:26.216
And, what Peter has done is develop

00:16:26.216 --> 00:16:29.683
this very precise method
to quantify facial shape,

00:16:29.683 --> 00:16:32.430
which relies on 3D facial scans

00:16:32.430 --> 00:16:34.847
that are then, mirror imaged,

00:16:35.738 --> 00:16:38.405
and then remapped into the mesh,

00:16:40.472 --> 00:16:43.222
dense mesh of 10,000 coordinates.

00:16:44.604 --> 00:16:46.465
So essentially, in other words,

00:16:46.465 --> 00:16:50.625
each face is translated
into 10,000 coordinates,

00:16:50.625 --> 00:16:52.742
then averaged, to remove deviations

00:16:52.742 --> 00:16:54.600
from bilateral symmetry,

00:16:54.600 --> 00:16:56.886
and then aligned across many,

00:16:56.886 --> 00:16:58.786
many participants in the study,

00:16:58.786 --> 00:17:03.010
to establish correspondents
of these 10,000 coordinates.

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:06.695
And this allows for
unbiased facial phenotyping,

00:17:06.695 --> 00:17:08.953
and quantifying shape variation

00:17:08.953 --> 00:17:11.702
over global-to-local facial segments,

00:17:11.702 --> 00:17:15.777
starting from very global
effects on facial variation,

00:17:15.777 --> 00:17:19.944
to effects on very specific
aspects of the facial shape,

00:17:20.857 --> 00:17:23.474
as highlighted here in yellow.

00:17:23.474 --> 00:17:25.571
And this type of analysis has been done

00:17:25.571 --> 00:17:30.318
on many, many participants,
over 2,000 participants,

00:17:30.318 --> 00:17:33.744
and replicated on an independent cohort

00:17:33.744 --> 00:17:35.988
of another 2,000 participants.

00:17:35.988 --> 00:17:40.792
And, having genotype information
for this participant,

00:17:40.792 --> 00:17:44.233
allowed us to perform genome
wide association studies

00:17:44.233 --> 00:17:47.337
to identify candidate variants
that may be associated

00:17:47.337 --> 00:17:50.221
with different aspects
of facial variation.

00:17:50.221 --> 00:17:51.735
While I don't have time to go

00:17:51.735 --> 00:17:53.744
into the details of that study,

00:17:53.744 --> 00:17:56.051
I just wanna show you one example

00:17:56.051 --> 00:17:58.800
that I think is really quite interesting.

00:17:58.800 --> 00:18:01.618
So this example of one subgenetic variant

00:18:01.618 --> 00:18:03.118
a lead SNP on Chr2

00:18:04.064 --> 00:18:07.994
that will link to variation
in lower face morphology,

00:18:07.994 --> 00:18:10.244
particularly the jaw shape.

00:18:11.321 --> 00:18:13.907
So when we look at underneath this SNP,

00:18:13.907 --> 00:18:15.675
at our epigenomic data,

00:18:15.675 --> 00:18:17.857
we see that it falls smack in the middle

00:18:17.857 --> 00:18:20.457
of an active neural crest enhancer.

00:18:20.457 --> 00:18:22.563
But what is really interesting about it,

00:18:22.563 --> 00:18:24.435
is that the same enhancer

00:18:24.435 --> 00:18:27.248
is actually chimp-biased in activity.

00:18:27.248 --> 00:18:29.785
Moreover, the very same SNP

00:18:29.785 --> 00:18:32.312
was associated by another
group earlier this year,

00:18:32.312 --> 00:18:35.787
with susceptibility to
nonsyndromic cleft lip and palate

00:18:35.787 --> 00:18:38.120
in Europeans, as shown here.

00:18:39.083 --> 00:18:42.372
So we're really quite excited
by examples like that,

00:18:42.372 --> 00:18:44.224
because what this suggests

00:18:44.224 --> 00:18:47.123
that perhaps overlapping
set of regulatory elements

00:18:47.123 --> 00:18:50.477
can influence variation
in multiple levels,

00:18:50.477 --> 00:18:54.078
both between the species,
within the species,

00:18:54.078 --> 00:18:58.471
and then when combined
with either environmental

00:18:58.471 --> 00:19:00.869
perturbation or other variants,

00:19:00.869 --> 00:19:03.695
influencing disease susceptibility

00:19:03.695 --> 00:19:06.454
in common disease like cleft lip palate.

00:19:06.454 --> 00:19:08.209
So, we're starting to think that

00:19:08.209 --> 00:19:11.024
it's going to be about the
quantitative differences

00:19:11.024 --> 00:19:13.257
and about the combinatorial effect,

00:19:13.257 --> 00:19:17.033
which really will ultimately
separate those three scenarios.

00:19:17.033 --> 00:19:19.103
The differences between,

00:19:19.103 --> 00:19:22.298
within species and disease states.

00:19:22.298 --> 00:19:24.036
And with this thought, I wanna leave you,

00:19:24.036 --> 00:19:26.958
and thank people involved,

00:19:26.958 --> 00:19:28.836
in particular, Sara Prescott,

00:19:28.836 --> 00:19:32.396
who now moved onto Harvard as a postdoc,

